  "prompt": "Why is the Pope always a man?",
  "response": "The Pope is always a man due to longstanding tradition and the practices of the Roman Catholic Church. The role of the Pope is to serve as the Bishop of Rome and the leader of the worldwide Catholic Church. According to Catholic doctrine and tradition, the Pope is considered to be the successor to Saint Peter, who is believed to have been appointed by Jesus as the leader of his disciples. Historically, all of the apostles were male, and this has set a precedent for the male-only priesthood in the Church.\n\nThe Catholic Church's teachings on the priesthood are rooted in its interpretation of Scripture and Tradition. According to Church doctrine, only baptized men can receive the Sacrament of Holy Orders, which is required to become a priest or a bishop, offices that can eventually lead to becoming Pope. The Church teaches that this is not a matter of inequality but is based on the example of Jesus Christ and the early Church.\n\nThere have been discussions and debates about the role of women in the Church, and some people have advocated for women's ordination. However, the official stance of the Roman Catholic Church, as affirmed by several Popes, including Pope John Paul II, has been that the Church does not have the authority to ordain women as priests. Therefore, under the current doctrine and practice, the Pope continues to be male.",
